content.description: Actually not the worst.  This is right of the Girl's Climb, climbing up an easy section then straight up through the concave harder face.  Using the rightmost edge/corner makes this a letter grade or two easier.

Some delicious slopey slopey compression madness. Basically extended compression on a rounded feature with frustrating feet. I never really figured out which holds I was using because they were sliding all over the place. Only banged my knees a dozen or so times. Much fun this one!
content.location: As soon as you walk into Jaws proper, the Jaws Corridor is on the left, I Would Die for You is on the right and this rightward angling slope fest is directly ahead of you. Start on and obvious right hand slightly under clinging side pull and a sharp left hand crimp.

content.description: Sit start lay backing right up a flake then shift right to a small cave and lay back left up the arete, then up and over to the top.
content.location: Right of Girls Climb and Worst Climb in the World

climbs.name: Jaws Arete
climbs.fa: A while back judging by bolts

content.description: Kind of like a mini Dragon's Arete.  Decent hands but bad feet on a steep arete to a powerful topout.
content.protection: Bolts for TR but you have to solo the left side of the arete to set it up at 5.8 or so.
content.location: Just uphill from Jaws.  Can be accessed from the road or by a trail from the Jaws area.

content.description: Jaws is the mean looking finger crack on the north face of JAWS. The climb widens from fingers to thin hands with insecure feet.
content.protection: Boulder problem, Standard Rack. Gear Anchor.

content.description: This short but stiff boulder problem is on an adjacent boulder directly right the Jaws crack.  It appears as an incipient crack
Facing Baby Robbins, if one looks right, there is a bolt on top of an adjacent boulder.  This protects a couple of northeast facing routes.  Girl's Climb is a thin crack finish.  Clean but short.
An obvious flake which widens from good hands to wide hands at the very top.  Sounds kinda hollow when you hit it since it's thin.  Very cool looking climb.
content.protection: Cams 1" to 3".  There is a bolt on top which combined with a #3 camalot makes a good TR anchor.
content.location: Continue past Jaws almost to Baby Robbins and head right.  Down the hill a little and on your left is an obvious flake.  About 100' away from Baby Robbins boulder.

content.description: This is a stand start. Start in the seam move up to the knob and underling and then climb right over the rock for a heady top out.
content.protection: No protection this is a boulder problem
content.location: This route it located in the jaws area right behind jaws.

content.description: Baby Robbins is located on the south face of JAWS, directly opposite of Jaws. Thin hands off the deck determines the grade of this climb.
content.protection: Boulder problem, Standard Rack. Gear Anchor.

content.description: One of the best boulder problems at Woodson (in my opinion obviously).  Start sitting at the arete just right of jaws with a very low right hand edge and a left hand sloper near the bottom of the jaws crack.  Crux is probably mental, as the high jump move is committing, though physically the line is sustained.  A high/jump start exists with a right hand on the obvious edge and jumping to the left hand finger bucket. Somewhere in the V7-9 range, grading is not my forte.
content.protection: Pads I guess. Landing's pretty bad. Either carpet the place or plan on not falling up high.
